  "summary": "Jirouchou reveals that Yashiro was actually Yuri, the daughter of the runaway Daiju, and a descendant of the Ichiyas bloodline. For thirty years, she had lived as a housekeeper under the name Tsukiyomi. It is suggested that Mochizuki knew her true identity as Daya and forced her to avoid using the Kono surname, leading her to live a life of hidden identity and atonement. The group concludes that the killer likely knew Tsukiyomi's true identity, as she had changed so significantly over three decades that even her own brothers could not recognize her.\n\nMcArthur arrives at the mansion accompanied by Kaname. When the narrator whispers to McArthur that \"Yamamoto is Hikari,\" McArthur reacts with visible shock, turning pale and dropping his walking stick. Despite this emotional distress, McArthur later hosts a meeting in the first-floor lounge for six attendees: Kikuchi, Kuroi, Yuzuha, Detective Tsujimura, Detective Horikawa, and the narrator.\n\nMcArthur addresses the murders of Ito and Uma, arguing that in a locked-room mystery, the motive (\"why\") is more important than the method (\"how\"). He begins a lecture on six categories of motives used to create a locked room to help identify the killer. He first rules out the motive of disguising a crime as a suicide, noting that Ito's head and Hama's body were found together in the room. He also rules out the motive of framing a specific person, as there was no indication the killer intended to point the finger at the deceased maid, Yashiro.",
